I don't know how New Yorkers pronounce it, but Polish people sure do it differently than the transcription you posted. The way the name sounds in our language is so Polish there is no way to transcribe it without those special letters used in dictionaries. The ś of Kościuszko has no equivalent sound in English, that I know of. We also never pronounce C as K. For us it's always a "ts"-ish sound. Our "sz" is your "sh". Our "u" is always your "oo". And "i " generally sounds like the English "ee". In the name Kościuszko all these sounds influence one another, too. kosh-CHYUUSH-koh sort of works but misses the "ś" sound, substituting "sh" for it. 

You can hear it in Polish here: <a href="https://pl.forvo.com/word/tadeusz_ko%C5%9Bciuszko" target="_blank">https://pl.forvo.com/word/tadeusz_ko%C5%9Bciuszko</a>/

@Andrzej

“The ś of Kościuszko has no equivalent sound in English, that I know of.”

Interesting! Any chance that sound is similar to the sound of the letter ž in Czech (which certainly has no equivalent in English)?

@Andrzej

Doh! I meant to ask about the Czech ř, which absolutely has no equivalent in English (or any other language I have studied, of which Czech is the only Slavic one). As I recall, it was quite challenging to learn to pronounce that sound when I was first introduced to Czech (15+ years ago).

But anyway, the Polish ś sounds a lot like the Czech š based on that audio (which I’d approximate in English with “sh”, though that’s probably dropping some nuance).

@Anonymous

No, no. Ś is nothing like sh. Well, ok, maybe it is, to some minor extent, but to a larger one it isn't, at all. I'd love 5 minutes with you in real life to make you see... Um... Hear? The light.

The Czech ř is our rz. The sound is exactly the same as the Czech ž and Polish ż. There are grammatical reason why we have two letters/letter combinations for the same sound. I won't go into the details as I lack the English vocabulary to describe them.

